data.content:
Here are the more idiomatic MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Better failure messages than Assert.IsTrue
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    CollectionAssert.Contains(users, users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`

MSTest doesn't have a built-in `All(predicate)` collection assert, so `Assert.IsTrue(collection.All(...), "message")` with a descriptive message is still the best option for predicate checks.
